uestions regarding the history of this period.Meeks explores a fascinating range of topics, from the figure of the androgyne in antiquity to the timeless matter of God’s reliability, from Paul’s ethical rhetoric to New Testament pictures of Christianity’s separation from Jewish communities. Meeks’ introduction offers a retrospective on New Testament studies of the past thirty years and explains the intersection of these studies with a variety of exploratory and revisionist movements in the humanities, embracing social theory, history, anthropology, and literature. In an epilogue the author reflects on future directions for New Testament scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianityxOrigin. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh1 aHilton, Allen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilton, Allen R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeeks, Wayne A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSnyder, H. Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSnyder, H. Gregory, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030009142740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013010240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300130102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300130102/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY